TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Causal Model of Linkages Among Environmental Dimensions, Macro Organizational Characteristics, and Performance
AU  - Keats, Barbara W.
AU  - Hitt, Michael A.
Y1  - 1988/09/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256460
DO  - 10.5465/256460
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 570
EP  - 598
VL  - 31
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - An integrative model of relationships among environmental dimensions, diversification strategy, firm size, structural divisionalization, and economic performance was developed and tested using environmental and organizational data from 110 large manufacturing firms. The results suggested that among those organizations, (1) higher levels of environmental instability were associated with lower levels of divisionalization and diversification, (2) strategy followed structure, and (3) size did not mediate the strategy-structure relationship. Furthermore, both environmental instability and diversification were positively related to market-determined performance, and instability was negatively related to operating performance. The results provided support for portions of each of three models, the external control, strategic management, and inertial models.
AB  - An integrative model of relationships among environmental dimensions, diversification strategy, firm size, structural divisionalization, and economic performance was developed and tested using environmental and organizational data from 110 large manufacturing firms. The results suggested that among those organizations, (1) higher levels of environmental instability were associated with lower levels of divisionalization and diversification, (2) strategy followed structure, and (3) size did not mediate the strategy-structure relationship. Furthermore, both environmental instability and diversification were positively related to market-determined performance, and instability was negatively related to operating performance. The results provided support for portions of each of three models, the external control, strategic management, and inertial models.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256460
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256460
Y2  - 2026/04/24
